    "body" : "<p>Java 7 introduces the <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/generics/types.html#diamond\">diamond syntax</a></p>\n\n<pre><code>Box&lt;Integer&gt; integerBox = new Box&lt;&gt;(); // Java 7\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>As compared to old java</p>\n\n<pre><code>Box&lt;Integer&gt; integerBox = new Box&lt;Integer&gt;(); // Before Java 7\n</code></pre>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>The critical reader will notice that this new syntax doesn't help with writing the for loops in the original question. That's correct and fully intentional it seems. See the other answer that cites Oracle's bug database.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 16698,
      "reputation" : 3349,
      "user_id" : 36661,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/00a07baedb1420bcf39a824439fc7a2b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Ajit George",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/36661/ajit-george"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 20,
    "last_activity_date" : 1606654637,
    "last_edit_date" : 1606654637,
    "creation_date" : 1462811854,
    "answer_id" : 37121016,
    "question_id" : 16132759,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In Java 8, you can use lambda type inference to avoid declaring the type.  The analogue to the questioner's examples would be:</p>\n<pre><code>object_array.forEach(obj -&gt; System.out.println(obj)); \nobject_array.forEach(obj -&gt; obj.do_something_that_only_this_particular_obj_can_do());\n</code></pre>\n<p>both of which can also be simplified using method references:</p>\n<pre><code>object_array.forEach(System.out::println); \nobject_array.forEach(ObjectType::do_something_that_only_this_particular_obj_can_do);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2756819,
      "reputation" : 1193,
      "user_id" : 2374651,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 57,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/tBTbI.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "samvel1024",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2374651/samvel1024"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 8,
    "last_activity_date" : 1508707355,
    "creation_date" : 1508707355,
    "answer_id" : 46879294,
    "question_id" : 16132759,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>It's not a pure Java solution, however adding a library called <a href=\"https://projectlombok.org/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">lombok</a> will enable the magic below to compile and work very much similar to <code>auto</code> keyword in C++</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; strList = Arrays.asList(\"foo\", \"bar\", \"baz\");\nfor (val s: strList){\n    System.out.println(s.length());\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
